    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-06-24T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-06-24T10:00:00-05:00" n="602"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d602">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">647.116/153: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Sydney</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moffat</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-06-24T11:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 24, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your June 10, 11 a.m. We contemplate recommending to the President suspending
                    application of trade agreement concessions to Australian products without
                    waiting for a reply to our note. It is essential before taking such action that
                    we have clear evidence that there is actual discrimination against American
                    trade. The Commercial Attaché’s telegraphic report of June 4<note n="19"
                        xml:id="d602fn19">Not found in Department files.</note> states that the
                    Sydney Customs Collector was granting permits for importation to many countries,
                    but was returning refused all applications relating to American products. Please
                    report by telegraph: (1) whether this practice is being continued, (2) whether
                    other customs collectors are following the same practice, and (3) whether this
                    practice applies to all or the greater part of the items on the prohibited list.
                    Please cite specific instances in which licenses for American products have been
                    refused while licenses for like products of other foreign non-British <pb
                        facs="0842" n="762" xml:id="pg_762"/> origin have been more or less
                    concurrently granted. Also please indicate whether you see any objection to
                    suspending generalization without waiting for a reply to our note referred to in
                    your telegram of June 10.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
